  "local_port": 46110,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am repairing a soft steel chair by arc welding and keep burning holes in the metal, what can I do to make a strong joint?",
  "response": "Burning holes in the metal during arc welding typically indicates excessive heat input or improper technique, especially when working with softer or thinner steel materials like those used in a chair. To achieve strong joints without burning through the metal, consider the following tips:\n\n1. **Choose the Right Electrode:**\n   - **Electrode Type:** Use electrodes suitable for mild or soft steel. For general-purpose welding, E6010 or E6011 might be appropriate, but for easier control and less penetration, E7018 electrodes are often preferred for their strength and versatility.\n   - **Electrode Size:** Opt for a smaller diameter electrode (e.g., 1/16\" or 3/32\") when working with thinner materials to reduce heat input and prevent burn-through.\n\n2. **Adjust Welding Current:**\n   - **Lower Amperage:** Reduce the welding current to match the thickness of the metal. Using too high of a current can concentrate heat in a small area, leading to burn holes.\n   - **Use a Balancing Technique:** If you're using a multi-pass approach, ensure each pass adds sufficient heat without excessive penetration.\n\n3. **Control Heat Input:**\n   - **Travel Speed:** Move at a steady, moderate speed. Moving too slowly allows more heat to accumulate, increasing the risk of burning through.\n   - **Electrode Angle and Distance:** Maintain the correct electrode angle (typically around 15-30 degrees from vertical) and keep a consistent arc length to distribute heat evenly.\n\n4. **Use Proper Technique:**\n   - **Weave Pattern:** Implement a slight weaving motion if appropriate, which can help distribute heat more evenly across the joint.\n   - **Multiple Passes:** Instead of trying to make a deep joint in one pass, use multiple shallower passes to build up the weld gradually.\n\n5. **Pre-Weld Preparation:**\n   - **Clean the Metal:** Ensure that the metal surfaces are clean and free from rust, paint, or contaminants, which can affect heat distribution and weld quality.\n   - **Fit-Up:** Ensure proper fit-up of the joint to minimize gaps, which can concentrate heat and lead to burn-through.\n\n6. **Consider Alternative Welding Methods:**\n   - **MIG or TIG Welding:** If possible, MIG (Metal Inert Gas) or TIG (Tungsten Inert Gas) welding might offer better control with less heat input compared to traditional Stick (Shielded Metal Arc) welding, especially for thinner materials.\n\n7. **Use Backing Materials:**\n   - **Backer Bars:** Employing a backing bar or using a copper backing can help absorb excess heat and prevent burn-through on the opposite side of the weld.\n\n8. **Practice and Technique Refinement:**\n   - **Practice Runs:** Before working on the actual chair, practice on scrap pieces of similar material to fine-tune your settings and technique.\n   - **Seek Feedback:** If possible, consult with experienced welders or refer to welding guides specific to thin or soft steel applications.\n\nBy carefully selecting your equipment, adjusting your settings, and refining your technique, you can achieve strong, clean welds without burning holes in the metal. Always prioritize safety by wearing appropriate protective gear and ensuring a well-ventilated workspace when welding.",
